            "id": "https://www.squareyards.com/blog/?p=31327",
            "url": "https://www.squareyards.com/blog/income-tax-exemption-invest-in-the-same-residence-claim-tax-reduction-under-section-54-and-54f",
            "title": "Income Tax Exemption: Invest in the Same Residence & Claim Tax Reduction Under Section 54 and 54F",
            "content_html": "\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">\u201cInvest in real estate today, hold it for a few years, and then sell it for a profit.\u201d This has long been the motto for investors seeking safe, low-risk, and low-volatility assets.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">When selling properties such as land, apartments, villas, flats, bungalows, etc. the owner nearly always makes a profit. This is especially true if the owner has owned the property for a long time. According to Indian tax rules, the profit earned is considered income, and the income-earner is responsible for paying taxes on it. While this is necessary, under different sections of the Income Tax Act, such sellers are entitled to specific exclusions from their tax liability.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The Income Tax Act, for instance, exempts long-term capital gains from taxation if they are invested in the acquisition or building of a residential property under two different sections, Section 54, and Section 54F. Many times, the question of whether a taxpayer can claim exemptions under both provisions if the investment is made in the same residential dwelling has been litigated.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-what-are-capital-gains\"><strong>What are capital gains?</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">When you sell an asset and make a profit, this is referred to as capital gains. The difference between the selling and buying price of an item is known as capital gains. Capital loss, on the other hand, occurs when you sell an item for less than the amount you paid for it. Because the gain or profit is classified as &#8220;income&#8221; under Indian Income Tax Regulations, the person who benefits from the sale must pay tax on the profit amount.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-what-is-the-capital-gains-account-scheme\"><strong>What is the Capital Gains Account Scheme?</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">If the asset is sold in Plan Year and the seller intends to buy a new house property before the time limit of 2 years or 3 years, the assesses must deposit the gains in the capital gains account scheme (in any branch of the public sector or bank) before the deadline for filing income tax returns.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">While claiming the deduction, the money previously spent on purchase/construction, as well as the amount put in the capital gains account plan, can be claimed as a cost.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">However, if the money put in the Capital Gains Account Scheme is not used within the time restriction, it will be considered income for the prior year in which the three-year period has expired (from the date of transfer of the original asset).</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-section-54-of-the-income-tax-act\"><strong>Section 54 of the Income Tax Act</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p>To qualify for the tax exemption under section 54, the taxpayer must meet the following requirements:</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 Individuals or Hindu Undivided Families (HUF) should be the taxpayers. Industries and corporations are not eligible for Section 54 tax advantages.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 It should be a residential property that is sold. Furthermore, the seller should acquire a new residential property one year before the transfer of the old property or two years following the transfer of the old property. If the seller is building a house instead of buying one, he or she must ensure that the new property&#8217;s construction is finished within three years of the sale/transfer date.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 It is recommended that the new residential property be acquired in India. If the bought property is located outside of India, the seller will not be entitled to any tax benefits.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-section-54f-of-the-income-tax-act\"><strong>Section 54F of the Income Tax Act</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">Taxpayers can get a tax reduction if they reinvest the net proceeds from the sale of a capital asset, according to Section 54F of the Income Tax Act. It should be emphasized that the capital asset sold under Section 54F should not be a residential property. Reinvestment in the acquisition or building of a residential property, however, is required to be eligible to claim exemption.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The means of capital gain is the main distinction between Section 54 and Section 54F of the Income Tax Act. If the capital gain is from the sale of a residential property, the exemption is under Section 54; alternatively, it is under Section 54F. Capital gains from the sale of assets such as bonds, shares, land, gold, and so forth may be subject to Section 54F.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-common-criteria-between-the-two-provisions\"><strong>Common criteria between the two provisions</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p>There are some parallels between the sections as well. If you invest in the acquisition or construction of residential property in India, you may take advantage of both of these sections.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 To be eligible for the exemption, a new residential house property must be acquired or built.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 The new residential property must be acquired one year before or two years after the property/asset is sold.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 Alternatively, for the construction of a house, both provisions demand completion of construction within three years after the asset&#8217;s selling date, regardless of when the work begins.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 If you are unable to invest the required amount in the way described above before the tax filing deadline or one year from the date of sale, deposit the specified amount.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 There are two separate sections, tax officials believe that in order to claim simultaneous investments, you must invest in two different residences and cannot claim the exemption if you just invest in one. The Hyderabad Tax Tribunal was able to address this issue.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-section-54-v-s-section-54f\"><strong>Section 54 v/s Section 54F</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Section 54</strong></td><td><strong>Section 54F</strong></td></tr><tr><td>If you are looking to claim full exemption, you must invest the entire capital gains.</td><td>To claim full exemption, all sale receipts should be invested.</td></tr><tr><td>If the entire capital gain is not invested, the uninvested portion is taxed as long-term capital gains.</td><td>If the entire sale proceeds are not invested, a proportional exemption is granted. <strong>&nbsp;</strong></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td>During the sale of the original asset, one should not own more than 1 residential property.</td></tr><tr><td>If you sell this new property within three years of acquisition, the exemption will be revoked, and capital gains on the sale will be taxed as short-term capital gains.</td><td>If you sell this new property within three years of its acquisition or construction. Or if you buy another residential property within two years of the sale of the original asset or construct a residential property other than the new house within three years of the sale of the original asset, this exemption will be revoked. The sale&#8217;s capital gains will be taxed as long-term capital gains.</td></tr><tr><td>A once-in-a-lifetime exemption is provided for investing in two properties providing capital gains.</td><td>No such exemption is available.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-what-is-the-maximum-amount-of-exemption-permitted-under-section-54-of-the-income-tax-act\"><strong>What is the maximum amount of exemption permitted under Section 54 of the Income Tax Act?</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The amount of the long-term capital gains tax exemption under Section 54 of the Income Tax Act will be the lesser of:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Long-term capital gains on the sale of a primary residence, or</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>The amount of money spent on the acquisition or building of a new residential home. As a result, any remaining capital gains (if any) will be taxed.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<h3 id=\"h-to-give-you-an-example\"><strong>To give you an example:</strong></h3>\n\n\n\n<p>John sells his villa (home) for \u20b945,00,000/-.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>He buys another villa for \u20b920,00,000/- using the profits of the sale.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The following is how capital gains will be calculated:</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Particulars</strong></td><td><strong>Amount (INR)</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Capital gain on the sale of a residential property</td><td>45,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Less: Invested in residential house property</td><td>20,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Balance \u2013 Capital Gains</td><td>25,00,000</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The exemption will be the lesser of \u20b945,00,000 in capital gains or \u20b920,00,000 in new property investment, therefore the exemption will be \u20b920,00,000.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-venkata-ramana-umareddy\"><strong>VENKATA RAMANA UMAREDDY</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-justify\">The assessee received long-term capital gain (LTCG) from the transfer of two different and independent assets \u2014 one a piece of land and the other a residential property \u2013 during the relevant financial year. He argued that because the whole LTCG from the sale of the two properties was invested in the acquisition of the new residential property, he was eligible for&nbsp;the exemptions provided by sections 54 and 54F. The Assessing Officer denied the application, stating that the assessee required to invest in two dwellings in order to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F. The CIT(A) also affirmed the AO&#8217;s decision. The current appeal was submitted by an aggrieved assessee.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-the-tribunal-ruled-in-the-assessee-s-favour-as-follows\"><strong>The Tribunal ruled in the assessee&#8217;s favour, as follows:</strong></h2>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 Sections 54 and 54F function separately and apply to LTCG deriving from the transfer of distinct and separate long-term capital assets. But only the acquisition or building of a new residential dwelling is exempt under both provisions.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>The lower authorities&#8217; sole rationale for rejecting the assessee&#8217;s claim of exemption under section 54 was that the assessee could not claim an exemption under both provisions for the same dwelling. As per the lower authorities, the assessee had to invest in two residences in order to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F. Such a reading of the regulations was completely erroneous and out of place.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 There was also no specific prohibition in either section 54 or 54F of the Act preventing the issuance of an exemption under both sections provided by the provisions&#8217; criteria.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u2022 The assessee was eligible to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F because the long-term capital gain emerged from the sale of two different and independent assets, namely, a residential house and a plot of land, and he had invested the entire capital gain in the purchase of a new residential property.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-you-might-also-like\">You Might Also Like</h2>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-yoast-seo-related-links\"><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/capital-gains-tax-exemption-section-54-in-a-nutshell-2\">Capital Gains Tax Exemption Section 54 in a Nutshell</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/simple-ways-for-nri-to-sell-property-in-india\">Simple ways for NRI to sell property in India</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/capital-gains-short-term-long-term\">Capital Gains: Short Term &amp; Long Term</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/learn-more-about-capital-gain-taxes\">Gain from Capital Gain: The Tax Benefit Angle</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/affordable-housing-the-new-growth-story-for-indian-real-estate\">Affordable Housing- the new growth story for Indian real estate</a></li></ul>\n\n\n\n<h2 id=\"h-frequently-asked-questions-faqs\">Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</h2>\n\n\n        <section class=\"sc_fs_faq sc_card\">\n            <div>\n\t\t\t\t<h2>How can I utilise sections 54 and 54F at the same time?</h2>                <div>\n\t\t\t\t\t                    <p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tDue to the numerous assets that fall under each area, these two sections are mutually exclusive and cannot be utilized at the same time. Depending on the asset, you will be eligible for either the Section 54 exemption or the Section 54F exemption.                    </p>\n                </div>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n\t        <section class=\"sc_fs_faq sc_card\">\n            <div>\n\t\t\t\t<h2>What is section 54F of the income tax act?</h2>                <div>\n\t\t\t\t\t                    <p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tSection 54F of the Income Tax Act provides for capital gain exemption in case of a long-term capital asset transfer in exchange for residential property investment.                    </p>\n                </div>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n\t        <section class=\"sc_fs_faq sc_card\">\n            <div>\n\t\t\t\t<h2>What are my capital assets?</h2>                <div>\n\t\t\t\t\t                    <p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tA capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their A capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their business. Capital assets are divided into three groups. First, there are movable and immovable capital assets, such as land, buildings, homes, and other real estates. Second, there are tangible and intangible capital assets, such as leasehold rights, cars, patents, and trademarks, among other things. Finally, there are fixed/circulating capital assets such as equipment, jewelry, and other such items.                    </p>\n                </div>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n\t        <section class=\"sc_fs_faq sc_card\">\n            <div>\n\t\t\t\t<h2>What are long-term capital assets?</h2>                <div>\n\t\t\t\t\t                    <p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\tA long-term capital asset is one that has been owned by a taxpayer for more than 36 months immediately before its transfer date. The term is 12 months, not 36 months, for certain assets such as units of equity-oriented mutual funds, shares, listed securities like debentures, units of UTI, Government bonds, and zero-coupon bonds. The advantages include: If an asset is classified as a long-term capital asset, the owner is entitled to indexation benefits. Furthermore, many exemptions are only applicable to long-term capital assets.                    </p>\n                </div>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n\t\n<script type=\"application/ld+json\">\n    {\n        \"@context\": \"https://schema.org\",\n        \"@type\": \"FAQPage\",\n        \"mainEntity\": [\n                    {\n                \"@type\": \"Question\",\n                \"name\": \"How can I utilise sections 54 and 54F at the same time?\",\n                \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n                    \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n                    \"text\": \"Due to the numerous assets that fall under each area, these two sections are mutually exclusive and cannot be utilized at the same time. Depending on the asset, you will be eligible for either the Section 54 exemption or the Section 54F exemption.\"\n                                    }\n            }\n            ,\t            {\n                \"@type\": \"Question\",\n                \"name\": \"What is section 54F of the income tax act?\",\n                \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n                    \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n                    \"text\": \"Section 54F of the Income Tax Act provides for capital gain exemption in case of a long-term capital asset transfer in exchange for residential property investment.\"\n                                    }\n            }\n            ,\t            {\n                \"@type\": \"Question\",\n                \"name\": \"What are my capital assets?\",\n                \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n                    \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n                    \"text\": \"A capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their A capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their business. Capital assets are divided into three groups. First, there are movable and immovable capital assets, such as land, buildings, homes, and other real estates. Second, there are tangible and intangible capital assets, such as leasehold rights, cars, patents, and trademarks, among other things. Finally, there are fixed/circulating capital assets such as equipment, jewelry, and other such items.\"\n                                    }\n            }\n            ,\t            {\n                \"@type\": \"Question\",\n                \"name\": \"What are long-term capital assets?\",\n                \"acceptedAnswer\": {\n                    \"@type\": \"Answer\",\n                    \"text\": \"A long-term capital asset is one that has been owned by a taxpayer for more than 36 months immediately before its transfer date. The term is 12 months, not 36 months, for certain assets such as units of equity-oriented mutual funds, shares, listed securities like debentures, units of UTI, Government bonds, and zero-coupon bonds. The advantages include: If an asset is classified as a long-term capital asset, the owner is entitled to indexation benefits. Furthermore, many exemptions are only applicable to long-term capital assets.\"\n                                    }\n            }\n            \t        ]\n    }\n\n</script><p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog/income-tax-exemption-invest-in-the-same-residence-claim-tax-reduction-under-section-54-and-54f\">Income Tax Exemption: Invest in the Same Residence &#038; Claim Tax Reduction Under Section 54 and 54F</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.squareyards.com/blog\">Real Estate News</a>.</p>\n",
            "content_text": "\u201cInvest in real estate today, hold it for a few years, and then sell it for a profit.\u201d This has long been the motto for investors seeking safe, low-risk, and low-volatility assets.\n\n\n\nWhen selling properties such as land, apartments, villas, flats, bungalows, etc. the owner nearly always makes a profit. This is especially true if the owner has owned the property for a long time. According to Indian tax rules, the profit earned is considered income, and the income-earner is responsible for paying taxes on it. While this is necessary, under different sections of the Income Tax Act, such sellers are entitled to specific exclusions from their tax liability.\n\n\n\nThe Income Tax Act, for instance, exempts long-term capital gains from taxation if they are invested in the acquisition or building of a residential property under two different sections, Section 54, and Section 54F. Many times, the question of whether a taxpayer can claim exemptions under both provisions if the investment is made in the same residential dwelling has been litigated.\n\n\n\nWhat are capital gains?\n\n\n\nWhen you sell an asset and make a profit, this is referred to as capital gains. The difference between the selling and buying price of an item is known as capital gains. Capital loss, on the other hand, occurs when you sell an item for less than the amount you paid for it. Because the gain or profit is classified as &#8220;income&#8221; under Indian Income Tax Regulations, the person who benefits from the sale must pay tax on the profit amount.\n\n\n\nWhat is the Capital Gains Account Scheme?\n\n\n\nIf the asset is sold in Plan Year and the seller intends to buy a new house property before the time limit of 2 years or 3 years, the assesses must deposit the gains in the capital gains account scheme (in any branch of the public sector or bank) before the deadline for filing income tax returns.\n\n\n\nWhile claiming the deduction, the money previously spent on purchase/construction, as well as the amount put in the capital gains account plan, can be claimed as a cost.\n\n\n\nHowever, if the money put in the Capital Gains Account Scheme is not used within the time restriction, it will be considered income for the prior year in which the three-year period has expired (from the date of transfer of the original asset).\n\n\n\nSection 54 of the Income Tax Act\n\n\n\nTo qualify for the tax exemption under section 54, the taxpayer must meet the following requirements:\n\n\n\n\u2022 Individuals or Hindu Undivided Families (HUF) should be the taxpayers. Industries and corporations are not eligible for Section 54 tax advantages.\n\n\n\n\u2022 It should be a residential property that is sold. Furthermore, the seller should acquire a new residential property one year before the transfer of the old property or two years following the transfer of the old property. If the seller is building a house instead of buying one, he or she must ensure that the new property&#8217;s construction is finished within three years of the sale/transfer date.\n\n\n\n\u2022 It is recommended that the new residential property be acquired in India. If the bought property is located outside of India, the seller will not be entitled to any tax benefits.\n\n\n\nSection 54F of the Income Tax Act\n\n\n\nTaxpayers can get a tax reduction if they reinvest the net proceeds from the sale of a capital asset, according to Section 54F of the Income Tax Act. It should be emphasized that the capital asset sold under Section 54F should not be a residential property. Reinvestment in the acquisition or building of a residential property, however, is required to be eligible to claim exemption.\n\n\n\nThe means of capital gain is the main distinction between Section 54 and Section 54F of the Income Tax Act. If the capital gain is from the sale of a residential property, the exemption is under Section 54; alternatively, it is under Section 54F. Capital gains from the sale of assets such as bonds, shares, land, gold, and so forth may be subject to Section 54F.\n\n\n\nCommon criteria between the two provisions\n\n\n\nThere are some parallels between the sections as well. If you invest in the acquisition or construction of residential property in India, you may take advantage of both of these sections.\n\n\n\n\u2022 To be eligible for the exemption, a new residential house property must be acquired or built.\n\n\n\n\u2022 The new residential property must be acquired one year before or two years after the property/asset is sold.\n\n\n\n\u2022 Alternatively, for the construction of a house, both provisions demand completion of construction within three years after the asset&#8217;s selling date, regardless of when the work begins.\n\n\n\n\u2022 If you are unable to invest the required amount in the way described above before the tax filing deadline or one year from the date of sale, deposit the specified amount.\n\n\n\n\u2022 There are two separate sections, tax officials believe that in order to claim simultaneous investments, you must invest in two different residences and cannot claim the exemption if you just invest in one. The Hyderabad Tax Tribunal was able to address this issue.\n\n\n\nSection 54 v/s Section 54F\n\n\n\nSection 54Section 54FIf you are looking to claim full exemption, you must invest the entire capital gains.To claim full exemption, all sale receipts should be invested.If the entire capital gain is not invested, the uninvested portion is taxed as long-term capital gains.If the entire sale proceeds are not invested, a proportional exemption is granted. &nbsp;&nbsp;During the sale of the original asset, one should not own more than 1 residential property.If you sell this new property within three years of acquisition, the exemption will be revoked, and capital gains on the sale will be taxed as short-term capital gains.If you sell this new property within three years of its acquisition or construction. Or if you buy another residential property within two years of the sale of the original asset or construct a residential property other than the new house within three years of the sale of the original asset, this exemption will be revoked. The sale&#8217;s capital gains will be taxed as long-term capital gains.A once-in-a-lifetime exemption is provided for investing in two properties providing capital gains.No such exemption is available.\n\n\n\nWhat is the maximum amount of exemption permitted under Section 54 of the Income Tax Act?\n\n\n\nThe amount of the long-term capital gains tax exemption under Section 54 of the Income Tax Act will be the lesser of:\n\n\n\nLong-term capital gains on the sale of a primary residence, or\n\n\n\nThe amount of money spent on the acquisition or building of a new residential home. As a result, any remaining capital gains (if any) will be taxed.\n\n\n\nTo give you an example:\n\n\n\nJohn sells his villa (home) for \u20b945,00,000/-.\n\n\n\nHe buys another villa for \u20b920,00,000/- using the profits of the sale.\n\n\n\nThe following is how capital gains will be calculated:\n\n\n\nParticularsAmount (INR)Capital gain on the sale of a residential property45,00,000Less: Invested in residential house property20,00,000Balance \u2013 Capital Gains25,00,000\n\n\n\nThe exemption will be the lesser of \u20b945,00,000 in capital gains or \u20b920,00,000 in new property investment, therefore the exemption will be \u20b920,00,000.\n\n\n\nVENKATA RAMANA UMAREDDY\n\n\n\nThe assessee received long-term capital gain (LTCG) from the transfer of two different and independent assets \u2014 one a piece of land and the other a residential property \u2013 during the relevant financial year. He argued that because the whole LTCG from the sale of the two properties was invested in the acquisition of the new residential property, he was eligible for&nbsp;the exemptions provided by sections 54 and 54F. The Assessing Officer denied the application, stating that the assessee required to invest in two dwellings in order to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F. The CIT(A) also affirmed the AO&#8217;s decision. The current appeal was submitted by an aggrieved assessee.\n\n\n\nThe Tribunal ruled in the assessee&#8217;s favour, as follows:\n\n\n\n\u2022 Sections 54 and 54F function separately and apply to LTCG deriving from the transfer of distinct and separate long-term capital assets. But only the acquisition or building of a new residential dwelling is exempt under both provisions.\n\n\n\nThe lower authorities&#8217; sole rationale for rejecting the assessee&#8217;s claim of exemption under section 54 was that the assessee could not claim an exemption under both provisions for the same dwelling. As per the lower authorities, the assessee had to invest in two residences in order to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F. Such a reading of the regulations was completely erroneous and out of place.\n\n\n\n\u2022 There was also no specific prohibition in either section 54 or 54F of the Act preventing the issuance of an exemption under both sections provided by the provisions&#8217; criteria.\n\n\n\n\u2022 The assessee was eligible to claim an exemption under sections 54 and 54F because the long-term capital gain emerged from the sale of two different and independent assets, namely, a residential house and a plot of land, and he had invested the entire capital gain in the purchase of a new residential property.\n\n\n\nYou Might Also Like\n\n\n\nCapital Gains Tax Exemption Section 54 in a NutshellSimple ways for NRI to sell property in IndiaCapital Gains: Short Term &amp; Long TermGain from Capital Gain: The Tax Benefit AngleAffordable Housing- the new growth story for Indian real estate\n\n\n\nFrequently Asked Questions (FAQs)\n\n\n        \n            \n\t\t\t\tHow can I utilise sections 54 and 54F at the same time?                \n\t\t\t\t\t                    \n\t\t\t\t\t\tDue to the numerous assets that fall under each area, these two sections are mutually exclusive and cannot be utilized at the same time. Depending on the asset, you will be eligible for either the Section 54 exemption or the Section 54F exemption.                    \n                \n            \n        \n\t        \n            \n\t\t\t\tWhat is section 54F of the income tax act?                \n\t\t\t\t\t                    \n\t\t\t\t\t\tSection 54F of the Income Tax Act provides for capital gain exemption in case of a long-term capital asset transfer in exchange for residential property investment.                    \n                \n            \n        \n\t        \n            \n\t\t\t\tWhat are my capital assets?                \n\t\t\t\t\t                    \n\t\t\t\t\t\tA capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their A capital asset is any property by an assessee that is either related to or unrelated to their business. Capital assets are divided into three groups. First, there are movable and immovable capital assets, such as land, buildings, homes, and other real estates. Second, there are tangible and intangible capital assets, such as leasehold rights, cars, patents, and trademarks, among other things. Finally, there are fixed/circulating capital assets such as equipment, jewelry, and other such items.                    \n                \n            \n        \n\t        \n            \n\t\t\t\tWhat are long-term capital assets?                \n\t\t\t\t\t                    \n\t\t\t\t\t\tA long-term capital asset is one that has been owned by a taxpayer for more than 36 months immediately before its transfer date. The term is 12 months, not 36 months, for certain assets such as units of equity-oriented mutual funds, shares, listed securities like debentures, units of UTI, Government bonds, and zero-coupon bonds. The advantages include: If an asset is classified as a long-term capital asset, the owner is entitled to indexation benefits. Furthermore, many exemptions are only applicable to long-term capital assets.                    \n                \n            \n        \n\t\nThe post Income Tax Exemption: Invest in the Same Residence &#038; Claim Tax Reduction Under Section 54 and 54F appeared first on Real Estate News.",
